Beyond Jool

What lies beyond the green giant?

0.7.1, no release yet.

Since the dawn of spaceflight, kerbals knew of 5 planets and 2 dwarf planets. Moho, Eve, Kerbin, Duna, Dres, Jool, and Eeloo. The Kerman Telescope, however, has found new bodies in the Kerbol System.

Beyond Jool is a planet mod I've been wanting to make since I bought the game. The idea is it would not add new stars, but add new planets, mainly a new Saturn analog. I'm fine with no Uranus or Neptune analogs. This thread is mainly for help. This year I finally did something with it.

The "version history" is here.

Spoiler

0.1 Added Sarkin.

0.2 Added Lull.

0.2.1 Fixed Sarkin lighting.

0.2.2 Fixed Lull fading.

0.3 Added Sushut.

0.4 Added Rage.

0.5. Added Pebble.

0.5.1 Gave Sushut atmosphere.

0.5.2 Removed Pebble (for now) and retextured Sushut.

0.6 Gave Sushut AtmosphereFromGround node and added Sapp and Kotta.

0.6.1 Made Kotta oblate. (Thanks Lt_Duckweed!) 

0.6.1.1 Extended Sapp's rings a bit. 

0.6.2 Fixed a crack in Sushut, because I had two VertexHeightMaps.

0.6.2.1 Made rings see through.

0.7  Readded Pebble, now named as Tom

0.7.1 Retextured Sushut AGAIN 

Sarkin is here

Spoiler

"Sarkin is the sixth planet in the Kerbol System, with it's large rings, and astounding size, it weird it hadn't been discovered... until now."

Lull is here.

Spoiler

"Lull is just a boring moon that looks a lot like the Mun. It, like the moons of Jool, was found after somekerb found a "grey dot" that wouldn't come off. However, its high inclination gives a nice view of Sarkin's rings."

Sushut is here.

Spoiler

"Sushut is massive. It has a small atmosphere, and is larger than Kerbin. It even has its own moon! It may be the hardest body to land on... It is named after the great planetary scientist Sushut Kerman, who figured out that Tylo was no mere smudge. (And then gave the tip to the KSC staff for that photo)"

Tom is here.

Spoiler

"A big rock. They say it was named after some other rock in a show? To be honest, the leading theory for the name is that the Kerbal Astronomical Society was running of good names."

 

Kotta is here.

Spoiler

is the third major moon of Sarkin. Its only major feature are its many valleys and canyons. Otherwise, it's just another moon."

Sapp is here.

Spoiler

" A cold, icy moon, Sapp's name is an accident, as it was supposed to be Sapphire, but by the time it was known, Sapp's name was already in many places. It has rings and even orbits retrograde! However, it is very hilly, with not a lot of flat land."

And Rage, a planet closer to the Sun then Moho.

Spoiler

"Rage. A planet so close to Kerbol you may go blind trying to find it. Some say it is more like Moho in the stories then Moho."

may nerf in future update, it takes like 4000 delta v to get there in a good transfer window.

To-do here-

1. Fix weird pole glitch.

2. Finish Sarkin system, maybe two more moons for a nice sounding "Sarkin Seven" (like a Jool 5!)

3. Oceans, for Rage. (lava)

4. Add a comet!

5. Moar dwarf planets next to Dres (maybe 3 or 2) And add more dwarfs beyond Sarkin. (3 maybe.)

6. Maybe add one more giant planet?

Beyond Jool uses a MIT License.

To install, download Kopernicus and dependancies into the Gamedata subfolder. Then insert the following folders from the zip file into Gamedata: 001_DuckweedUtils, Beyond Jool, MitchellNetravali (inside 000_NiakoUtils).

Pics here.

Spoiler

Things explode on teleportation.

Couple of things:  the scaled space mesh for your planet (which is used in map view, or when far away or zoomed out in standard view) is stored in the cache file at BeyondJool/Cache/Kotta.bin.

Anytime you change the PQS (such as by adding the oblate PQS mod) you must delete the cache file, so that Kopernicus will generate a new one.

Secondly, your current period is too low.
Using this google doc https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1QSUjAmyAIACKAFSL_C8qv5GxYc4YTB1eDBRP4TTUl5A/edit?usp=sharing, I input your body's radius and the shortest possible stable period is 6877 seconds.  Any  faster than this, and the body, if it were actually being physically simulated, would tear itself apart.

Edited July 26 by Lt_Duckweed
